    <h1>Introduction to HTML</h1>

<h2>What is HTML?</h2>
<p>HTML stands for HyperText Markup Language. It is the standard markup language used to create web pages. HTML consists of a series of elements that describe the structure of a web page.</p>

<h2>Basic Structure of an HTML Document</h2>
<p>An HTML document has a basic structure that includes several key elements:</p>
<ul>
    <li><strong>&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;</strong> - Declares the document type and version of HTML.</li>
    <li><strong>&lt;html&gt;</strong> - The root element that contains all the other HTML elements.</li>
    <li><strong>&lt;head&gt;</strong> - Contains meta-information about the document, such as the title and links to CSS files.</li>
    <li><strong>&lt;title&gt;</strong> - Sets the title of the document, which appears in the browser's title bar or tab.</li>
    <li><strong>&lt;body&gt;</strong> - Contains the content of the document, such as text, images, links, etc.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Key HTML Elements</h2>
<p>Some of the most commonly used HTML elements include:</p>
<ul>
    <li><strong>&lt;h1&gt; to &lt;h6&gt;</strong> - Heading tags used to create headings. &lt;h1&gt; is the highest (most important) level, and &lt;h6&gt; is the lowest.</li>
    <li><strong>&lt;p&gt;</strong> - Defines a paragraph.</li>
    <li><strong>&lt;a&gt;</strong> - Defines a hyperlink, which is used to link from one page to another.</li>
    <li><strong>&lt;img&gt;</strong> - Embeds an image in the page.</li>
    <li><strong>&lt;ul&gt; and &lt;ol&gt;</strong> - Defines unordered (bulleted) and ordered (numbered) lists, respectively.</li>
    <li><strong>&lt;div&gt;</strong> - A block-level container used to group content and apply styles.</li>
</ul>

<h2>How HTML Works</h2>
<p>HTML is used to create the structure of a web page. It does this by using "tags" that surround the content and tell the browser how to display that content. Tags usually come in pairs: an opening tag (e.g., &lt;p&gt;) and a closing tag (e.g., &lt;/p&gt;). The content between the tags is what will be displayed on the web page.</p>

<h2>Example of a Simple HTML Document</h2>
<p>Here is an example of a simple HTML document:</p>
<pre>
&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;
&lt;html&gt;
    &lt;head&gt;
        &lt;title&gt;My First HTML Page&lt;/title&gt;
    &lt;/head&gt;
    &lt;body&gt;
        &lt;h1&gt;Hello, World!&lt;/h1&gt;
        &lt;p&gt;This is my first web page.&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;
</pre>

<h2>Conclusion</h2>
<p>Understanding the basics of HTML is essential for anyone interested in web development. HTML is the foundation of the web, and knowing how to use it will allow you to create your own web pages and start building more complex websites.</p>
    
    
